==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic, from Indo-European ''*egom'' ‘I’, from a presumed form ''*eg''.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian [[ik]], Old Saxon [[ik]] (Dutch [[ik]]), Old High German [[ih]] (German [[ich]]), Old Norse [[ek]] (Swedish [[jag]]), Gothic [[𐌹𐌺]].  The IE root, in various forms, is also the source of Sanskrit [[अहम्]], Latin [[ego]] (Spanish [[yo]] etc.), Greek [[εγώ|ἐγώ]], Lithuanian [[eo]], Avestan ''azəm'', Old Church Slavonic ''az’'' (Russian [[я]]), Latvian [[es]], Arminian [[es]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /iʧ/

===Personal Pronoun===
'''iċ'''
# [[I]], used by the speaker referring to himself or herself as the subject, or in agreement with that subject

